  <div class="article-section">

    <h2>Step 1 — Check Your BMI First</h2>
    <p>Before working out calories, you need a clear picture of where you stand. BMI (Body Mass Index) gives you a quick read on whether your current weight is in a healthy range for your height.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>BMI Range</th><th>Category</th><th>What it means for calories</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Below 18.5</td><td>Underweight</td><td>Calorie surplus needed — aim for slow weight gain</td></tr>
        <tr><td>18.5 – 24.9</td><td>Normal weight</td><td>Maintenance calories — focus on body composition</td></tr>
        <tr><td>25.0 – 29.9</td><td>Overweight</td><td>Moderate deficit — 300 to 500 kcal below TDEE</td></tr>
        <tr><td>30.0+</td><td>Obese</td><td>Structured deficit — 500 to 750 kcal below TDEE</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>For people of Asian descent, the overweight threshold starts at BMI 23 rather than 25. Check your number using our <a href="bmi-calculator.html">BMI Calculator</a> or the <a href="asian-bmi-calculator.html">Asian BMI Calculator</a> if applicable.</p>

    <h2>Step 2 — Calculate Your TDEE</h2>
    <p>TDEE stands for Total Daily Energy Expenditure — the number of calories your body burns in a day including all activity. This is your baseline. To lose weight you eat below it. To gain weight you eat above it. To maintain, you match it.</p>

    <p>TDEE is calculated in two steps. First, your BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate) — the calories burned at rest — is estimated using the Mifflin-St Jeor formula:</p>

    <div class="formula-box">
      <span>Men:</span> BMR = (10 × weight kg) + (6.25 × height cm) − (5 × age) + 5<br>
      <span>Women:</span> BMR = (10 × weight kg) + (6.25 × height cm) − (5 × age) − 161
    </div>

    <p>BMR is then multiplied by an activity factor to get TDEE:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Activity Level</th><th>Multiplier</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Sedentary (desk job, little exercise)</td><td>× 1.2</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Lightly active (exercise 1–3 days/week)</td><td>× 1.375</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Moderately active (exercise 3–5 days/week)</td><td>× 1.55</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Very active (hard exercise 6–7 days/week)</td><td>× 1.725</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Skip the manual calculation — use our <a href="calorie-calculator.html">Calorie Calculator</a> to get your TDEE instantly.</p>

    <h2>Step 3 — Set Your Calorie Target Based on BMI Goal</h2>
    <p>Once you know your TDEE and your BMI, you can set a realistic calorie target. The relationship between calorie deficit and weight loss is well established: a deficit of approximately 7,700 calories produces 1 kg of fat loss.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Goal</th><th>Calorie Target</th><th>Expected rate</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Slow loss (safer for older adults)</td><td>TDEE − 300 kcal</td><td>~0.3 kg/week</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Standard loss</td><td>TDEE − 500 kcal</td><td>~0.5 kg/week</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Faster loss (BMI over 30)</td><td>TDEE − 750 kcal</td><td>~0.75 kg/week</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Maintenance</td><td>= TDEE</td><td>No change</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout"><p>💡 Never go below 1,200 kcal/day for women or 1,500 kcal/day for men. Eating too little slows metabolism, causes muscle loss, and makes the deficit unsustainable.</p></div>

    <h2>Worked Example — From BMI to Calorie Target</h2>
    <p>Here's a full worked example to show how BMI and calorie calculation connect in practice.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Detail</th><th>Value</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Person</td><td>Female, 42 years old</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Height</td><td>163 cm (5'4")</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Current weight</td><td>78 kg</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Current BMI</td><td>29.3 (overweight)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Goal BMI</td><td>23.0 (upper normal)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Goal weight</td><td>61 kg</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Weight to lose</td><td>17 kg</td></tr>
        <tr><td>BMR (Mifflin-St Jeor)</td><td>1,512 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>TDEE (lightly active × 1.375)</td><td>2,079 kcal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Target calories (−500 deficit)</td><td>1,579 kcal/day</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Expected timeline at 0.5 kg/week</td><td>~34 weeks (8 months)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>How Many Calories to Drop One BMI Point?</h2>
    <p>A useful way to think about this: each BMI point corresponds to roughly 2.5 to 3 kg for most adults (depending on height). At a deficit of 500 kcal/day losing 0.5 kg/week, dropping one BMI point takes approximately 5 to 6 weeks.</p>

    <p>For reference at common heights:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Height</th><th>Weight per 1 BMI point</th><th>Time to drop 1 BMI point (at −500 kcal/day)</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>155 cm</td><td>~2.4 kg</td><td>~5 weeks</td></tr>
        <tr><td>163 cm</td><td>~2.7 kg</td><td>~5–6 weeks</td></tr>
        <tr><td>170 cm</td><td>~2.9 kg</td><td>~6 weeks</td></tr>
        <tr><td>178 cm</td><td>~3.2 kg</td><td>~6–7 weeks</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>BMI and Calories for Asian Populations</h2>
    <p>If you are of Asian descent, your healthy BMI ceiling is 22.9 rather than 24.9. This means the calorie deficit needed to reach a healthy BMI is somewhat larger than the standard chart suggests. A person of Chinese, Malay, or Indian descent with a BMI of 26 is two full BMI points into the overweight range under Asian guidelines, not just one.</p>
    <p>Use the <a href="asian-bmi-calculator.html">Asian BMI Calculator</a> to find your correct target weight first, then plug that into the calorie calculation.</p>

    <h2>Beyond Calories — What Else Affects BMI</h2>
    <p>Calories in versus calories out is the primary driver of weight change, but several other factors affect how quickly BMI responds.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Sleep — poor sleep increases hunger hormones (ghrelin) and reduces satiety hormones (leptin), making deficit harder to maintain</li>
      <li>Stress — chronic stress elevates cortisol, which promotes fat storage particularly around the abdomen</li>
      <li>Muscle mass — building muscle raises BMR, meaning you burn more calories at rest over time</li>
      <li>Protein intake — higher protein diets preserve muscle during a deficit and increase satiety</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="warn-callout"><p>⚠️ BMI and calorie calculators provide estimates based on population averages. Individual metabolism varies. If you have a medical condition affecting weight or metabolism, consult a doctor or registered dietitian before making significant dietary changes.</p></div>

